**Section 1: User Story
**

**1.1** **Epic Story**

As a Notice Processing Officer who needs to follow up against notices in the OCMS, I want the OCMS to follow up against individuals/companies with reminders sent but returned to us for specific reasons, so that notices under the IDs will temporarily stop processing while investigation is pending.

**1.2 User Stories **

![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

**1.3 Key Functions &amp; Features**

| Functions | Description |
| --- | --- |
| Manage Unclaimed Reminders | Unclaimed Reminders refer to Reminder Letters to Offenders that have been returned to URA as the Offender is no longer residing at the address or did not claim their mail. OCMS Staff Portal and backend allows OICs to record returned letters and temporarily suspend affected notices under TS-UNC while OICs check whether there is an updated address. |
| Manage Notices when Offenders cannot be located | If no new address is found for the Offender, OICs may manually apply a TS-HST (House Tenant) suspension to the affected Notice by recording the Offender as an HST ID. The Offender’s ID will also be recorded in the HST table, which serves two purposes: To support monthly MHA/DataHive checks for updated address data, and To allow OCMS to automatically suspend new Notices involving the same Offender and prevent Reminder Letters from being sent to invalid addresses. |

**Section 2: Manage Unclaimed Reminders 
**

**2.1** **Use Case**

- Unclaimed Reminders refer to Reminder Letters that have been returned to URA as the Offender is no longer residing at the address or did not claim their mail. 

- The OCMS Staff Portal has an Unclaimed module that allows OCMS OICs to: Fill in the Unclaimed Reminder form on screen so that it can be generated by the backend as an Unclaimed Reminder Report for user to download 
- Trigger the OCMS backend to apply the TS-UNC suspension and save the return details in OCMS 
- Retrieve and download the Unclaimed Batch Data Report from the backend to view the Offender particulars returned by MHA and DataHive

- When the TS-UNC suspension is initiated from the Portal, the OCMS Backend will: Update the following data to the corresponding RDP or DN record in the database: Date of Return
- Reason for Return
- Remarks on Envelope
- Generate the Unclaimed Reminder Report
- Apply the TS-UNC suspension to the Notice with the Unclaimed Reminder
- Save the return details in the Request Driver Particulars, Driver Notice and Suspended Notice tables
- Schedule the Notice for Offender Particulars check with MHA and DataHive to identify if there is a new address so that OICs can decide if another Reminder Letter should be sent.
- An Unclaimed Batch Data Report will be generated when the data from MHA and DataHive is returned.

- Important points to note:When the Unclaimed Reminder Report is generated for export, the Report file will be stored in the file storage so that the file can be retrieved by the OIC for viewing. 
- There is no requirement from users to store the Unclaimed Batch Data Report data in the database. 
- When the Unclaimed Batch Data Report is generated, the Report file will be stored in the file storage so that the file can be retrieved by the OIC for viewing.

**2.3** **Record Unclaimed Reminders Screen**

- The Unclaimed Reminders Screen is a function of the Unclaimed Screen module in the OCMS Staff Portal. 

- The key function of the module is to allow OICs to record Reminder and Court Letters that could not be delivered and have been returned to URA. 

- The Unclaimed Screen lets OICs record the details related to an Unclaimed Letter, for example: Type of Letter
- Notice number 
- Date of Reminder 
- Offender’s ID Number (auto populated from RDP/DN table) 
- Offender Name (auto populated from RDP/DN table)
- Date of Return
- Reason for Return
- Remarks on Envelope
- Suspension Remarks

- After the user has entered the details for the Unclaimed Letter and submitted the details to the OCMS backend, the backend will: Generate an Unclaimed Reminder Report in Excel format which lists the Unclaimed data entered by the user and auto populated by OCMS
- Store the Unclaimed Reminder Report Excel file in the file storage, so that it can be retrieved for user download
- Return the file download URL to the Staff Portal so that it can be downloaded onto the OIC’s laptop for archival.
- The details of the Unclaimed Reminder Report will not be stored in the OCMS Database, except for the ‘Date of Return’, ‘Reason for Return’, ‘Remarks on Envelope’ and ‘Suspension Remarks’ fields, which will be stored in the RDP/DN/Suspended Notice DB tables. OCMS will alsostore the download URL of the report file in the database. 

- Following the submission, OCMS will apply TS-UNC suspension to the relevant notices and query MHA and DataHive to retrieve the Unclaimed Offender’s latest address and particulars for manual follow up. 

- The data retrieved from MHA and DataHive will be used to generate an Unclaimed Batch Data Report which OICs will use for manual follow-ups.

| 6 | Add TS-UNC Records to Report List | The updated records are added to the list for generating the Unclaimed Reminder Report. |

| 13 | Put Notice numbers for NRIC to ocms_adhoc _nro_queue | OCMS adds the Notice numbers to the ocms_adhoc_nro_queue database table to prepare for submission to MHA for particulars check. Note: The standard MHA enquiry and result crons will be modified to send/process Offender IDs for Notices that: Are scheduled to enter the next processing stage Are listed in an Unclaimed Reminder Report and require an address check Have been suspended with TS-HST and are scheduled for the monthly address check Require an address check after the TS-NRO suspension expires The standard MHA result cron will be modified to include the Datahive enquiry for NRIC, FIN and UEN after MHA results are processed. |

**2.4.6 Accessing Unclaimed Reminder Reports**

The Unclaimed Reminder Report can be retrieved in 2 ways: 

- Upon submission of an Unclaimed Reminder online form, it will be downloaded automatically after the submission has been processed by the OCMS Backend

- Via the Report Module &gt; Unclaimed Reminder where the user can select a date range to retrieve the reports generated during the defined period.

**2.4.6.1 Auto Download Upon Unclaimed Reminder Submission**

When an Unclaimed Reminder online form has been submitted, the OCMS generates the report and returns the report URL so that the Staff Portal can download the report automatically. Refer to Section 2.4.1. 

**2.4.6.2 Manual Download from Staff Portal Report Module **

- The Staff Portal Report module has a function where users can select the Unclaimed Reminder Report to view the reports in the system. 

- Users begin by selecting a date range to retrieve reports generated during the selected period. 

- The Staff Portal queries the new ocms_unclaimed_report database to retrieve the results based on the following parameters: unc_report_type = 1 – Unclaimed Reminder Report
- unc_report_date date range start date 
- unc_report_date date range end date 

- Results retrieved will be displayed in a table on screen with the following fields: 

| Field | Description | Sample Value | Functionality |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Date of Report | Date of report generation | 22/03/2025 | |
| Report Generated By | Name of Officer | John Lee | |
| Action | Button for user to trigger Report download | | On click, page calls the URL file URL to download the report |

**2.5** **Backend Processing for Unclaimed Reminder Batch Data Report**

The processing for the Unclaimed Reminder Batch Data Report will leverage the standard MHA and DataHive data query processes to retrieve the Offenders particulars. 

**2.5.1 Processing Flow 
**![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.

![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

| No. | Process | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| | Pre-condition Offender ID added to ocms_temp_nro_queue | Offender IDs from the Unclaimed Reminder Report and HST IDs are inserted into ocms_temp_nro_queue for scheduled MHA/DataHive checks. The Batch Data Report process is triggered by the scheduled MHA and DataHive crons. |
| 1 | MHA Enquiry Cron starts | Cron retrieves NRICs for stage change (ocms_valid_offence_notice, ocms_offence_notice_owner_driver) and IDs from ocms_temp_nro_queue. It generates the MHA enquiry file and drops it to SFTP. |
| 2 | MHA Results Processing Cron starts | When results are returned, OCMS detects whether the record is for stage change processing or Unclaimed Reminder or HST ID processing: If it is for stage change processing, OCMS continues along the standard flow (refer to MHA processing in OCMS 8) to update Owner, Hirer or Driver particulars. If it is for Unclaimed Reminders or HST ID processing, OCMS stores the address ocms_temp_unc_hst_addr. |
| 3 | Continue to DataHive Query | OCMS queries DataHive for NRIC, FIN, and UEN for Unclaimed Reminders. |
| 4 | DataHive Results Processed | When results are returned, OCMS detects whether the record is for stage change processing or Unclaimed Reminder or HST ID processing: If it is for stage change processing, OCMS continues along the standard flow (refer to MHA processing in OCMS 8) to update Owner, Hirer or Driver particulars. If it is for Unclaimed Reminders or HST ID processing, OCMS stores the address ocms_temp_unc_hst_addr. |
| 5 | Consolidate Results | OCMS consolidates MHA and DataHive results in ocms_temp_unc_hst_addr. |
| 6 | Generate Report | OCMS generates the Unclaimed Batch Data Report. |
| 7 | Upload Report | Report is uploaded to Azure Blob Storage and a file URL is generated. |

**Section 3: HST Suspension 
**

**3.1** **Use Case**

- Following the review of unclaimed offenders’ latest addresses (refer to Section 2.5), OICs may apply a TS-HST suspension to a Notice by recording the ID as HST if the address retrieved from MHA or DataHive matches the address used for the Unclaimed Reminder Letter.

- This scenario typically arises when the offender (house tenant) has relocated but failed to update their particulars with the relevant government agencies.

- After an ID is added to the HST table and the Notice(s) is suspended with TS-HST, OCMS performs a monthly query to MHA and DataHive to determine if a new address is available. 

- If a new address is available, OCMS will notify the OIC via the monthly reports so that the OIC can perform the following follow-up actions: Update the Offender’s address 
- Revive the TS-HST suspension 
- The OCMS Staff Portal has an HST module that allows OCMS OICs to: Create an HST record for an Offender ID and trigger a TS-HST to all outstanding Notices under the ID
- Update the Offender’s name and/or address in the HST table 
- Revive all TS-HST suspensions under the ID and remove the Offender’s HST record 

- When a HST record is created, all outstanding Notices under the ID will be suspended with TS-HST. 

- The OCMS backend has a set of pre-defined tasks that will be performed automatically: Suspend all new notices under the ID with TS-HST before they enter the RD1 processing stage
- Query MHA and Datahive on the first calendar day of each month to check whether a new address is available and notify the OIC via a Work Item Report if a new address is available. 
- Re-apply the TS-HST suspension immediately after the existing suspension expires

**3.2** **High-Level Process Flow for HST Processing**

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

| No. | Process | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| | Pre-condition No new address found for Offender | After reviewing the Unclaimed Batch Data Report (refer to Section 2.5.3) or public feedback and confirming that there is no new address, the OIC may add the offender ID as an HST ID via the OCMS Staff Portal. |
| 1 | Create HST Suspension | The OIC manually applies the TS-HST suspension to HST ID, and this triggers the backend to: Automatically create the Offender’s ID as an HST ID Query the database to retrieve all non-court and outstanding Notices in which the HST ID is the Current Offender Auto suspend all Notices returned by the query with TS-HST. OCMS proceeds to Step 2. Refer to Section 3.3. |
| 2 | Create Offender as HST ID and Suspend All Notices Under ID with TS-HST | Upon receiving the request from the Staff Portal, the OCMS backend proceeds to: Add the Offender ID to the HST database table Query the database to retrieve all non-court and outstanding Notices in which the HST ID is the Current Offender Apply TS-HST to all outstanding Notices under the offender ID which are not permanently suspended. This prevents the system from sending Reminder Letters to an invalid address. Offender IDs added to the HST database table are used to identify and suspend new offence notices associated with the HST ID (Step 3). Refer to Section 3.4. |
| 3 | Background Task New Notices under ID suspended TS-HST Pre-RD1 | New Notices under the same ID will be suspended with TS-HST: After sending the eNA SMS or email at the ENA Processing Stage, before entering RD1. Before sending the Offender ID to MHA/DataHive as part of the preparation for RD1 Refer to the OCMS 11 NOPO Processing Functional Document. |
| 4 | Payment Made? | A Notice suspended with TS-HST remains payable despite the suspension. If payment is made, OCMS will proceed to permanently suspend the Notice with PS-FP, without reviving the TS-HST suspension, to stop the Notice Processing. If no payment is made, the Notice remains suspended. Once the TS-HST suspension expires, OCMS proceeds to Step 5. |
| 5 | Background Task Apply Looping TS-HST | OCMS backend will reapply a new TS-HST suspension automatically when the current one expires (looping behavior). Refer to the OCMS 17 Temporary Suspension Functional Document. |
| 6 | Monthly MHA and DataHive Checks &amp; Reports (CRON) | A scheduled cron job runs on the first calendar day of each month to query MHA and DataHive for the latest address and other details linked to each HST ID. When results are returned, OCMS compares the new address with the existing one to determine if a new address is available. If the address is unchanged, the Notice continues to be suspended. When the TS-HST suspension expires, OCMS proceeds to Step 5. If the address has changed, OCMS adds the record to the Work Item Report which is generated after the query is completed for user review and follow up in Step 7. Refer to Section 3.5. |
| 7 | Manual HST Update | The OIC may manually update the offender's name or address in the HST table via the Staff Portal. Once updated, the new name/address details replace the existing ones in the HST database table. Refer to Section 3.6. |
| 8 | Manual HST Revive | The OIC manually lifts the TS-HST suspension for all outstanding Notices for the Offender ID via the Staff Portal, allowing them to resume the standard processing workflow. The HST ID is then removed from the HST database, ensuring that new Notices under the offender ID are no longer suspended prior to entering the RD1 processing stage. Refer to Section 3.5 |
| 9 | End | The HST processing workflow concludes. |

**3.3** **Manual HST Suspension **

- The Manual HST Suspension is a function of the HST module in the OCMS Staff Portal. 

- The key function of Manual HST Suspension is to allow OICs to:Automatically suspend all outstanding Notices under the ID with TS-HST to stop Notice Processing temporarily, so that Reminder Letters will not be sent to the existing address which is invalid 

- Add the Offender’s ID as an HST ID, so that OCMS can suspend new Notices under the ID in the future 

- The function lets OICs review and edit information related to the Offender’s address before confirming the TS-HST suspension, for example: Name
- Address
- Date of Address Change
- Invalid Address Tag
- Address Indicator

| ENA Qualification process determines that Notice does not qualify for eNotification and the Next Processing Stage will be patched to RD1. | Triggered By: LTA Result Processing Cron Notice Last Processing Stage: ROV |
| After the eNotification (SMS/email) initial send is successful. | Triggered By: eNotification Sending Cron Last Processing Stage: ENA |
| After the eNotification (SMS/email) re-send is successful. | Triggered By: Retry eNotification Cron Last Processing Stage: ENA |
| After the eNotification (SMS/email) re-send is unsuccessful. | Triggered By: Retry eNotification Cron Last Processing Stage: ENA |
| When the eSevice Furnished Application is synched from the Internet to the Intranet for processing | Triggered By: Sync Furnished Submissions cron Last Processing Stage: The stage at which the Furnished Submission was synced |
| When eService furnished submission is auto approved and new offender is furnished | |
| When eService furnished submission is manually approved by OIC and new offender is furnished | |
| When OIC furnishes a new Offender via the OCMS Staff Portal | Triggered By: OIC via OCMS Staff Portal Last Processing Stage: The stage at which the Furnish was triggered |
| OIC redirects the Notice to another existing Offender via the OCMS Staff Portal | Triggered By: OIC via OCMS Staff Portal Last Processing Stage: The stage at which the Redirect was triggered |
| PLM furnishes a new Offender via the PLUS Staff Portal | Triggered By: PLM via PLUS Staff Portal Last Processing Stage: The stage at which the Furnish was triggered |
| PLM redirects the Notice to another existing Offender via the PLUS Staff Portal | Triggered By: PLM via PLUS Staff Portal Last Processing Stage: The stage at which the Redirect was triggered |

**3.3.7.2 HST Check Outcomes and System Actions**

| Offender ID listed in ocms_hst database table? | System Action |
| --- | --- |
| Yes | OCMS checks whether the Notice meets the conditions for TS-HST suspension. If the Notice has an active PS suspension or in in a Court stage after CPC, Notice will not be suspended. If the Notice is not permanently suspended and is not in a Court Stage after CPC, OCMS backend proceeds to suspend the Notice with TS-HST |
| No | Notice continues along the processing workflow that triggers the HST ID Check. |

- The purpose of the check and suspension is to avoid sending Reminder Letters to Offenders whose addresses have been determined as invalid.

**3.5** **Manual HST Revival **

- The Manual HST Revival is a function of the HST module in the OCMS Staff Portal. 

- The key function of Manual HST Revival is to allow OICs to:Edit the HST Offender’s name and address
- Lift all TS-HST Suspensions for outstanding Notices under the HST ID
- Delete the HST ID from the ocms_hst database table

**3.5.1 User Journey for Manual HST Revival**

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.

**![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)**

| No. | Step | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | OIC Launches Staff Portal | OIC navigates to the HST module in the OCMS Staff Portal |
| 2 | OIC Selects “Manual HST Revival” function | OIC selects the option to perform a manual HST (TS-HST) revival. |
| 3 | OIC Enters Offender ID | OIC inputs the offender’s ID number. The Staff Portal automatically detects and populates the ID type. |
| 4 | Staff Portal initiates query to OCMS Backend to check if Offender ID is a HST ID | The Staff Portal queries the OCMS Backend using the Offender ID to check if the Offender’s ID is listed in the ocms_hst database: If the Offender’s ID is not listed in the database, OCMS proceeds to Step 5 If the Offender’s ID is listed in the database, OCMS proceeds to Step 6. |
| 5 | Scenario: Offender ID is not an HST ID | The Staff Portal displays a pop-up message “ID is not suspended under HST.” |
| 6 | Scenario: Offender ID is an HST ID | Staff Portal displays the Offender’s name and the latest address details returned by MHA/DataHive. |
| 7 | OIC reviews and/or edit Offender’s details | OIC reviews and/or edit the address details returned from MHA/DataHive. |
| 8 | OIC initiates HST revival | OIC clicks the “Revive HST” button to initiate the revival of all TS-HST suspensions on Notices under the HST Offender’s ID. |
| 9 | Staff Portal triggers the OCMS Backend to revive the TS-HST suspension | OCMS Staff Portal sends the request to the OCMS backend to delete the Offender’s ID record in the HST database table and revive the TS-HST suspensions under the Offender’s ID. If HST ID deletion fails, OCMS Backend will respond to the Staff Portal without reviving the TS-HST suspension. OCMS proceeds to Step 10. If HST ID deletion is successful, OCMS proceeds to Step 11. |
| 10 | Scenario: Delete HST ID fails | If HST ID deletion fails, the Staff Portal displays the following message “Unable to delete HST ID. Notices were not revived.” |
| 11 | Scenario: Delete HST ID is successful | OCMS Backend proceeds to revive* all outstanding Notices under the Offender’s ID. If revival fails for one or more Notices, OCMS Backend will skip the Notice(s) and log the error. It will continue to process the rest of the Notices. If a suspension was revived successfully for one or all Notices, OCMS will log the success. OCMS Backend proceeds to Step 12 after all Notices have been processed. *HST revival only revives TS-HST and not other suspension codes. |
| 12 | OCMS Staff Portal displays the suspension statuses | OCMS Staff Portal displays the result of the TS-HST revival and HST ID deletion “ HST ID deleted successfully. HST revival has been applied to the following Notices”. The page will display a table listing the Notices that have been processed for TS-HST revival, with the corresponding success/failed status. |
| 13 | End | The process concludes. |

**3.5.7 TS-HST Revival Follow Up Action**

- After the TS-HST suspension is lifted, the revived Notices will continue to be processed along the standard Notice Processing Workflow. 

- Upon revival, OCMS Backend will perform the follow-up action to check if the Notice’s Next Processing Date has passed: If the Next Processing Date has passed, the OCMS Backend will generate the Reminder Letter for the Next Processing Stage at the scheduled time and move the Notice to the next stage thereafter.

- If the Next Processing Date is a future date, the Notice will continue along the workflow until it has reached the scheduled time to generate the Reminder Letter for the Next Processing Stage and move the Notice to the next stage thereafter.
**3.6** **HST Reports**

OCMS generates 4 types of reports to assist OICs in their monitoring of address changes for HST Offenders: 

- Monthly HST Data Report 
- Monthly HST Work Items Report (customised data)
- Ad-hoc Report for HST Hirer/Driver Furnished 
- Ad-hoc Report for Alternative Address Furnished/Updated for New Notice Under HST ID

**3.6.1 Monthly HST Data Report **

- The Monthly HST Data Report is auto generated by the OCMS Backend after it completes the retrieval of HST Offenders’ latest particulars from MHA and DataHive on the first calendar day of each month.
- The report captures the latest offender particulars, such as name and address, returned by MHA and DataHive. 

**3.6.1.1 Processing Flow for Generating Monthly HST Data Report**

- The process for generating the report is the same as that of the Unclaimed Reminder Batch Data Report listed in Section 2 – Manage Unclaimed Reminders. 

- *Refer to Sections 2.5.1 and 2.5.2 of this document for details. *
- The generated Report will be sent to the OIC via email and will also be downloadable from Staff Portal. 

**3.6.1.2 Sample Report**

*The format of the Monthly HST Data Report is the same as the Unclaimed Reminder Batch Data Report. Refer to Section 2.5.4 for the sample report.
*

**3.6.2 Monthly HST Work Items Report**

- The Monthly HST Work Items Report is auto generated by the OCMS Backend after it has completed processing the HST Offenders’ latest particulars from MHA and DataHive on the first calendar day of each month.

- The report outlines the following processing outcomes: No. of NRIC with no record returned from MHA
- No. of NRIC deceased + notices PS-ed under 'RIP/RP2'
- No. of NRIC with change in address and/or invalid address tag
- No. of FIN deceased + notices PS-ed under 'RIP/RP2'
- No. of FIN granted citizenship/PR
- No. of FIN with no address found
- No. of FIN with multiple addresses
- No. of FIN with change in address
- No. of UEN with no record returned
- No. of UEN with change in address
- Total no. of HST records 

- The outcomes listed in the report allow the OIC to determine the next steps for processing the corresponding HST IDs, for example: To update the HST Offender’s Mailing Address with the new address 
- To remove the Monthly Offender from the HST database table and revive all HST suspensions under the Offender’s ID
- To redirect the Notice 
- To change the suspension to PS-RIP or RP2 if the HST Offender has died

**3.6.4 Ad-hoc Report for Alternative Address Furnished/Updated for New Notice Under HST ID**

- The Ad-hoc Report for Alternative Address Furnished/Updated is: Generated and sent to OICs daily via email and work item 
- Manually downloaded by the OIC via the Staff Portal’s Report module. 

- The Report lists the HST IDs (Owners, Hirers or Drivers) who: Are Current Offenders of Notices that were suspended with TS-HST; AND
- Have received an updated address on the current date via the LTA Returned Data (Owners only) that is different from the address in the ocms_hst database table; OR
- Have been furnished as an Offender with a mailing address on the current date via the Furnish Hirer/Driver eService (Hirers and Drivers only) that is different from the address in the ocms_hst database table; OR
- Have been furnished as an Offender with a mailing address on the current date via the OCMS Staff Portal (Hirers and Drivers only) that is different from the address in the ocms_hst database table; OR
- Have been furnished as an Offender with a mailing address on the current date via the PLUS Staff Portal (Hirers and Drivers only) that is different from the address in the ocms_hst database table

- The report will display the particulars of the Offender, the address listed in the HST database and the furnished/updated address.
